
String Object:

1) var name='Bhaskar jyoti gogoi';

2) String object has some properties and methods :

    Property                Description
 1) length              Returns number of characters in the string.
 
    Method                  Description
 1) toUpperCase()       Changes string to uppercase characters(eg, name to NAME).
 2) tolowerCase ()      Changes string to lowercase characters.
 3) charAt()            Takes an index number as a parameter, and returns the character found at that position.
 4) indexOf()           Returns index number of the first time a character or set of characters is found within the string.
 5) lastIndexOf()       Returns index number of the last time a character or set of characters is found within the string.
 6) substring()         Returns characters found between two index numbers where the character for the first index number is included and the character for the last index number is not included. eg, name.substring(8,14);
 7) split()             When a character is specified, it splits the string each time it is found, then stores each individual part in an array.
 8) trim()              Removes whitespace from start and end of string.
 9) replace()           It takes one value that should be found, and another to replace it (by default, it only replaces the first match it finds). eg, name.replace('sk','w');

   eg,  <p id="info">saying="Home sweet home"</p>
        <script>
            var saying='Home sweet home';
            var msg='<h2>length</h2><p>'+saying.length+'</p>';
            msg+='<h2>uppercase</h2><p>'+saying.toUpperCase()+'</p>';
            msg+='<h2>lowercase</h2><p>'+saying.toLowerCase()+'</p>';
            msg+='<h2>character at index 12</h2><p>'+saying.charAt(12)+'</p>';
            msg+='<h2>first ee</h2><p>'+saying.indexOf('ee')+'</p>';
            msg+='<h2>last e</h2><p>'+saying.lastIndexOf('e')+'</p>';
            msg+='<h2>character index 8 to 14</h2><p>'+saying.substring(8,14)+'</p>';
            msg+='<h2>replace</h2><p>'+saying.replace('me','w')+'</p>';
            var el=document.getElementById('info');
            el.innerHTML=msg;

        </script>






































